For example this should be allowed:


         alias a = array<f32,select(1,2,5==6)>;

Right now any '=' code point will terminate a template candidate.  It should only do so if it's actually an assignment, or compound assignment. But we should allow comparisons that involve '=' in the token.

What are the rules of applying [[interpolate]] to non user-defined variables?

1. When is applied to entry point function parameters or entry point return type:
As entry point function parameters and return type are decorated with a builtin or [[location]]. The question is if we want to allow, [[builtin(...), interplate(...)]], eg.
```
[[stage(fragment)]]
fn frag_main([[interpolate(flat), builtin(position)]] input : vec4<f32>) {}
```

ps. it cannot directly apply to a vertex shader return type since vertex shader return type must include [[builtin(position)]].

2. When applied to a member of a structure type:
Do we allow these?
```
struct S {
  [[interpolate(flat), builtin(position)]] m : vec4<f32>; 
  [[interpolate(flat)]] n : vec4<f32>; 
};
```

How about when it is used?
```
struct Out {
  [[interpolate(flat), builtin(position)]] m : vec4<f32>; 
};

[[stage(vertex)]]
fn vtx_main([[location(0)]] input : vec4<f32>) -> Out 
{
  return Out();
}
```

All these will be clarified if spec says: "Must only be applied to user-defined IO".

@toji, #1810 introduced the [`GPUPresentationContext`](https://gpuweb.github.io/gpuweb/#presentation-context) with a `configure` method that takes a nullable dictionary as argument:
```
undefined configure(GPUPresentationConfiguration? configuration);
```

Nullable dictionary arguments are [not allowed in Web IDL](https://heycam.github.io/webidl/#idl-nullable-type): "Although dictionary types can in general be nullable, they cannot when used as the type of an operation argument or a dictionary member". This makes the Web IDL checker sad.

